[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] The `LayoutShift` interface of the Performance API provides insights into the layout stability of web pages based on movements of the elements on the page.
[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] A layout shift happens when any element that is visible in the viewport changes its position between two frames.
[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] These elements are described as being **unstable**, indicating a lack of visual stability.
[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] The Layout Instability API provides a way to measure and report on these layout shifts.
[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] All tools for debugging layout shifts, including those in the browser's developer tools, use this API.
[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] The API can also be used to observe and debug layout shifts by logging the information to the console, to send the data to a server endpoint, or to web page analytics.
[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] Performance tools can use this API to calculate a CLS score.
[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] Always returns `0` (the concept of duration does not apply to layout shifts).
[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] Returns a `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time when the layout shift started.
[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] Returns the layout shift score calculated as the impact fraction (fraction of the viewport that was shifted) multiplied by the distance fraction (distance moved as a fraction of viewport).
[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] Returns `true` if `lastInputTime` is less than 500 milliseconds in the past.
[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] Returns the time of the most recent excluding input (user input that would exclude this entry as a contributor to the CLS score) or `0` if no excluding input has occurred.
[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] Returns an array of `LayoutShiftAttribution` objects with information on the elements that were shifted.
[src:core-web-vitals/api-layoutshift] The following example shows how to capture layout shifts and log them to the console.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] Since December 2025, this feature works across the latest devices and browser versions.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] This feature might not work in older devices or browsers.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] The `LargestContentfulPaint` interface provides timing information about the largest image or text paint before user input on a web page.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] The key moment this API provides is the Largest Contentful Paint (LCP) metric.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] It provides the render time of the largest image or text block visible within the viewport, recorded from when the page first begins to load.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] To measure render times of other elements, use the `PerformanceElementTiming` API.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] `LargestContentfulPaint` inherits from `PerformanceEntry`.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] To get an accurate measurement of render time for cross-origin resources, set the `Timing-Allow-Origin` header.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] See Cross-origin image render time and Use startTime over renderTime for more details.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] The element that is the current largest contentful paint.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] The time the element was rendered to the screen.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] May be a coarsened value if the element is a cross-origin image loaded without the `Timing-Allow-Origin` header.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] The intrinsic size of the element returned as the area (width * height).
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] This property returns an empty string when there is no id.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] Returns the `timestamp` when the rendering phase ended and the paint phase started.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] Returns the `timestamp` when the painted pixels were actually drawn on the screen.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] If the element is an image, the request url of the image.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] Returns the value of this entry's `renderTime`.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] Returns `0`, as `duration` is not applicable to this interface.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] Returns a JSON representation of the `LargestContentfulPaint` object.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] In the following example, a `PerformanceObserver` is registered to get the largest contentful paint while the page is loading.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] The `buffered` flag is used to access data from before observer creation.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] The LCP API analyzes all content it finds (including content that is removed from the DOM).
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] When new largest content is found, it creates a new entry.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] It stops searching for larger content when scroll or input events occur, since these events likely introduce new content on the website.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] Thus the LCP is the last performance entry reported by the observer.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] The `paintTime` and `presentationTime` properties enable you to retrieve specific timings for the paint phase starting and the painted pixels being drawn on the screen.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] The `paintTime` is broadly interoperable, whereas the `presentationTime` is implementation-dependent.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] This example builds on the earlier observer example, showing how to check for `paintTime` and `presentationTime` support and retrieve those values if they are available.
[src:core-web-vitals/largest-contentful-paint-api] In non-supporting browsers, the code retrieves the `renderTime` or `loadTime`, depending on what is supported.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Faster website download speeds have been shown to increase visitor retention and loyalty and user satisfaction, especially for users with slow internet connections and those on mobile devices.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Web performance also leads to less data travelling across the web, which in turn lowers a website's power consumption and environmental impact.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Some aspects which can affect the speed of page load include browser/server cache, image optimization, and encryption (for example SSL), which can affect the time it takes for pages to render.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] The performance of the web page can be improved through techniques such as multi-layered cache, light weight design of presentation layer components and asynchronous communication with server side components.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] In the first decade or so of the web's existence, web performance improvement was focused mainly on optimizing website code and pushing hardware limitations.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] According to the 2002 book *Web Performance Tuning* by Patrick Killelea, some of the early techniques used were to use simple servlets or CGI, increase server memory, and look for packet loss and retransmission.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Although these principles now comprise much of the optimized foundation of internet applications, they differ from current optimization theory in that there was much less of an attempt to improve the browser display speed.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Steve Souders coined the term "web performance optimization" in 2004.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] At that time Souders made several predictions regarding the impact that WPO as an "emerging industry" would bring to the web, such as websites being fast by default, consolidation, web standards for performance, environmental impacts of optimization, and speed as a differentiator.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] One major point that Souders made in 2007 is that at least 80% of the time that it takes to download and view a website is controlled by the front-end structure.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] This lag time can be decreased through awareness of typical browser behavior, as well as of how HTTP works.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Web performance optimization improves user experience (UX) when visiting a website and therefore is highly desired by web designers and web developers.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] They employ several techniques that streamline web optimization tasks to decrease web page load times.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] This process is known as front end optimization (FEO) or content optimization.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] In addition to the techniques listed below, the use of a content delivery network—a group of proxy servers spread across various locations around the globe—is an efficient delivery system that chooses a server for a specific user based on network proximity.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Typically the server with the quickest response time is selected.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Web browsers open separate Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) connections for each Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) request submitted when downloading a web page.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] These requests total the number of page elements required for download.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] However, a browser is limited to opening only a certain number of simultaneous connections to a single host.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] To prevent bottlenecks, the number of individual page elements are reduced using resource consolidation whereby smaller files (such as images) are bundled together into one file.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] This reduces HTTP requests and the number of "round trips" required to load a web page.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Web pages are constructed from code files such JavaScript and Hypertext Markup Language (HTML).
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] As web pages grow in complexity, so do their code files and subsequently their load times.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] File compression can reduce code files by about 40 percent, thereby improving site responsiveness.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Web Caching Optimization reduces server load, bandwidth usage and latency.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] CDNs use dedicated web caching software to store copies of documents passing through their system.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Many website platforms, such as SiteGround, IONOS, Wix, and Hostinger, rely on global CDNs and caching technologies to deliver faster page loads across different geographical regions.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Subsequent requests from the cache may be fulfilled should certain conditions apply.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Web caches are located on either the client side (forward position) or web-server side (reverse position) of a CDN.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Web browsers are also able to store content for re-use through the HTTP cache or web cache.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Requests web browsers make are typically routed to the HTTP cache to validate if a cached response may be used to fulfill a request.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] If such a match is made, the response is fulfilled from the cache.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] This can be helpful for reducing network latency and costs associated with data-transfer.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] The HTTP cache is configured using request and response headers.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Code minification distinguishes discrepancies between codes written by web developers and how network elements interpret code.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Minification removes comments and extra spaces as well as crunch variable names in order to minimize code, decreasing files sizes by as much as 60%.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] In addition to caching and compression, lossy compression techniques (similar to those used with audio files) remove non-essential header information and lower original image quality on many high resolution images.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] These changes, such as pixel complexity or color gradations, are transparent to the end-user and do not noticeably affect perception of the image.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Another technique is the replacement of raster graphics with resolution-independent vector graphics.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Vector substitution is best suited for simple geometric images.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Lazy loading of images and video reduces initial page load time, initial page weight, and system resource usage, all of which have positive impacts on website performance.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] It is used to defer initialization of an object right until the point at which it is needed.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] The browser loads the images in a page or post when they are needed such as when the user scrolls down the page and not all images at once, which is the default behavior, and naturally, takes more time.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Since web browsers use multiple TCP connections for parallel user requests, congestion and browser monopolization of network resources may occur.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Because HTTP/1 requests come with associated overhead, web performance is impacted by limited bandwidth and increased usage.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Instead of a website's hosting server, CDNs are used in tandem with HTTP/2 in order to better serve the end-user with web resources such as images, JavaScript files and Cascading Style Sheet (CSS) files since a CDN's location is usually in closer proximity to the end-user.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] In recent years, several metrics have been introduced that help developers measure various aspects of the performance of their websites.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Modules to measure metrics such as TTFB, FCP, LCP, FP etc are provided with major frontend JavaScript libraries such as React, NuxtJS and Vue.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] Google publishes a library, the core-web-vitals library that allows for easy measurement of these metrics in frontend applications.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] In addition to this, Google also provides the Lighthouse, a Chrome dev-tools component and PageSpeed Insight a site that allows developers to measure and compare the performance of their website with Google's recommended minimums and maximums.
[src:core-web-vitals/web-performance] In addition to this, tools such as the Network Monitor by Mozilla Firefox help provide insight into network-level slowdowns that might occur during transmission of data.
